Let's write awk code ensuring no leading comma.

awk script:

awk '{
  if ($3=="/boot/efi" && $1 !~ /^#/) {
    # remove any existing nosuid
    gsub(/nosuid/, "", $4);
    # remove any trailing commas
    sub(/,$/, "", $4);
    if ($4 != "") $4=$4",nosuid"; else $4="nosuid";
  }
  print
}' /etc/fstab > /tmp/fstab.tmp && mv /tmp/fstab.tmp /etc/fstab

This will work if $4 has options. For our case: options field = "umask=0077,shortname=winnt". It will produce "umask=0077,shortname=winnt,nosuid". Good.

Edge: if options had trailing comma? Unlikely, but gsub may remove nosuid but may leave leading/trailing comma. Sub removes trailing. We don't remove leading.

